Home!

Back to your shitty old apartment! Back to the cold pipes and being messy and the place where your problems are so comfortable. 

Home!

Back to the man who loves you! Bye to your college town, college friends, vows said and toasts given, everyone married and the candles packed up and a one way ticket to Burbank, him smiling in the driver’s seat. 

Ten years ago you lived there. For a week you try your old hometown on for size, so pretty but too small for you. 

Nineteen year old me, you have no idea— you’d be so miserable if you got everything you wanted. 

I love you, though!

You text your mom from the airport in the state you grew up in: I’m on my way home.

MERRY BIRTHDAY MOMMY!!!
MERRY CHRISTMAS TO ALL and to all a great night!!!

One last Christmas in this house. The five of us still up at three in the morning because it doesn’t count as over until we go to bed. 

Sitting on the floor in front of the tree even though it’s too cold to be there, too late to be there, too sad to be there, just because next year we won’t have the chance to be there.

A week in my house with the same friends who spent their summers here, married to each other and living down the road. 

Movie nights at the house that they built from the ground up and then Dom and I go home hand in hand to my childhood bedroom. I exist here but only in the past. 

Nostalgia for today, tomorrow. Nostalgia for next Christmas when I look back at these pictures and realize it’s a place I’ll never go back to. It all happened in a place I’ll never go back to. 

Is there anything specific about being born to these coordinates, here in this marsh by the coast in the south where it’s warm when it rains? What did it do to me that I lived here all my life until I didn’t? 

Will it still be my hometown with no home?

I find Kristen standing in my room alone. “This room!” she says. “It could be the last time I’m in here.” Do either of us remember the first?

It feels an awful lot like the last episode of a sitcom and I can’t bear to watch the last ten minutes. Everyone off in different directions when we used to meet up here. 

It’s such a small thing, I’m sure, to lose the house that you grew up in. 

It’s just that I’ve never done it.

22 things I learned in 2022

1. What’s ahead is just as good (if not better) than what came before.

2. Pre register for Taylor swift tickets!!!!

3. Go where you are loved. 

4. If you work as hard as you possibly can and then you luck out once, they’ll say everything happened because you put in the work. Remember what it felt like to work that hard before you were lucky. 

5. Holding on to things only works for as long as you have the storage.

6. Pick the aisle seat if you know you’ll have to pee.

7. Don’t just keep saying you’re going to do it someday. At some point you’re going to have to start. 

8. Call your grandparents. Call your parents. Ask them questions. They don’t want to bother you. You call. 

9. If you expect good things you notice good things.

10. Eat before a shot. (I mean the medical kind, but also the other kind, too.)

11. Let yourself be loved. You don’t have to be combative in the face of kindness. You don’t even have to deserve it. But if it’s there, you might as well enjoy it. 

12. You can say goodbye a hundred times and never feel like you got it just right. It doesn’t have to be just right.

13. Sometimes sharing a failure feels even better than sharing a success. 

14. If you’re visiting a new city check to see if they have a botanical garden and leave a morning free for it.

15. Let it happen to them without worrying about if it will happen to you, too. The fact that it happened to them actually has no affect on the chances of it happening to you. It only feels like it does. 

16. If you really want to commit to a workout routine pick a tv show that you only let yourself watch while you work out. 

17. Write a speech for every wedding you go to. Even if you don’t have to give a speech, they’ll love it just as much (and maybe more) in the card. 

18. It’s better to be kind than anything else, and you are completely in control of how kind you are. 

19. The worst person to disappoint is yourself. 

20. If you want to remember a night fondly, add some dancing to it.

21. You know the right timing. It’s in there. Just listen for it.

22. Don’t wait until you’re leaving to notice you’ll be missed.
hello 2023 💙🌙✨

Sometimes it feels like I only have time for one thing before the migraine descends and sends me back to bed again. 

The hours shrink. The days and weeks shrink, too. All that time you thought you had stretching out before you, and what will you do with it?

Exercise? Do the dishes? Catch up on emails? See a friend? Drive yourself to a doctor’s appointment? 

Today you just write this. 

And you look back over the months and there’s no progress. Only constant struggle to stay in the exact same spot. Only countless hours alone in the dark, trying to soothe the one thing that always demands your attention. 

Please, can I have some of it back? Can I borrow it, just for an hour, just to do something that I like? Just to do my laundry?

Sometimes I look at my life and think I’d like to do more. Am I losing something? Am I wasting it?

Sometimes I look at my life and think I’m trying to do too much. Shouldn’t I plan around my pain? Shouldn’t I make things as easy on myself as possible? 

What’s the line between giving up and self care? What the line between being young and sick? 

They say we all have the same twenty-four hours in our day. Is it really that many? Twenty-four seems like a luxury. 

At this point I’ll settle for two.

happiness as a form of rebellion

I wish they looked at me as a whole person, not a puzzle they have to solve, my pain an inconvenience on their way back from lunch. 

I wish I was more to them than the organ bringing down the sum of my parts. The faint air of irritation, the eye roll that accompanies any mention of another factor of my personhood. 

When you bite down the sob and say “It hurts so bad I can’t sleep through the night,” and the doctor nods politely and tells you that doesn’t fall under their specialty. 

I am a good girl who does all of her paperwork ahead of time. I am a good girl who arrives fifteen minutes early and always has her copay and speaks in a clear firm voice. I ask the right questions and only cry when I’m desperate. 

I wish they could see what it does to the good girl who has always minded her parents, always got A’s and people pleased and said yes to everything anyone asked of her, how it slices away at the perfectionist girl to sit on a table and be told over and over how difficult you are simply for existing. How keeping your body working for you is such a problem for everyone. 

I don’t love medicine, you want to say. I’m not the person in the room who chose this as a life. I am the one that it happened to.

Every doctor is so mad when they see the list of all my surgeries. I color code it to make it easier. I bring highlighters. I nod and smile and apologize for being sick. 

I am so sorry, always. 

The attitude, like it’s rude for me to bring up my pain. Like it’s rude for me to push back and say no, actually that wasn’t helping. It didn’t work. Like I’m calling them wrong. The way it bruises an ego, to believe me. 

And I accept it gratefully. I have no choice. I thank them for their time, every time. I pay up. I make the next appointment, put it into my calendar, make a note to arrive fifteen minutes early.

art o’clock

One last return trip. Spoiled is the woman who gets to sleep in a room surrounded by relics of her girlhood. After thirty years the exhibit is closing.

We dig through the artifacts. Look at this, I say to Kristen, who played with the dolls and the teacups and remembers yellow and green walls. Remember this? I ask Chloe, who saw me through the red-penned journals of my teen years. God, I used to be dramatic, I say to Dom as I sob into the piles of my old things. Can you even believe it? 

I feel embarrassed of how long I’ve gotten to keep this childhood bedroom and also jealous of everyone who gets longer. How dare I be lucky in this way.

I’m a terror— everyone tiptoes around the complicated feelings that radiate off me and leave my hair standing up straight. 

Exhume your girlhood; choose what stays and what goes. Send your parents off to their new home in which you will be a guest. 

I remember growing up here so vividly. I was so strange and sick and discontented with all my comforts. It feels exactly like it is, to swallow barbed-wire tears in a bed full of your favorite teddy bears. I wish I was crying on a cliff somewhere in the wind. This just feels ridiculous. 

Do I say goodbye to the girl I was, and how? Do I bring her with me? Is she always with me, or is part of her tucked under the same comforter in the blue room, frozen in time? I think I left her there for safekeeping. I always knew I could come back for her. 

I went through thirty years of journals, school papers, and notes passed between friends. I was searching for growth and changes and found all the ways I stayed exactly the same. Things that I thought I invented about myself that it seems were fundamental. 

I leave tomorrow. And I’ll come back— I’ll come back. But I won’t come home.

So dramatic. I always was. :)

The other day I was talking about all the past lives I might have lived— where I was, who I was, what I did. How I think my mom and Kristen take it in turns to be my mother and my best friend. Or maybe I was their mom. We all get jumbled up, but we’ve loved each other for a long time now. 

Dom listened for a while with the patience of someone who has heard me say most everything once or twice already. “What about me?” he said.

“Oh, I always find you.”

In every lifetime. In every story. In every version. 

That’s why I got that tingle when I met him. It wasn’t love— not yet. But it was familiar. Like standing in front of a stranger and thinking “I’ve been here before.”

For all the nights I cried in this room over everything, all of it, and the weight of it that I carried myself, imagining someone like you there to hold me. You were a secret comfort. One day I would find you and everything hard would be made easier.

And now to be at the end of my twenties back in this bed, and the tears feel teenage, and my secret hope came true. The very thing I always asked for. Holding me, and comforting me over the loss of all the rest of it. 

Why am I crying for a time before I got the things I wanted? 

It’s so superfluous and slow, this loss of something that was never mine to lose. My old life was discarded for the new, but still I liked the look of it, my past a dollhouse dusty on my shelf. 

I liked to take it down from time to time just to look around.

And this feels like the most indulgent moment yet— to make you board a plane and hold my hand and come back to the place I said I was happy to leave and watch me cry tears of pity for how lonely you have made every moment seem in retrospect. 

You know I used to fall asleep holding my own hand?

I wish I was exaggerating. 

I’ve been so wrong about so many things I hoped for. Almost all of them. 

But four years ago you sat on my couch in the new place I call home and every hard thing was made easier. Every single one.

the kind of friendship that heals all old wounds and insecurities. the kind of friendship where you can be a kid again, be annoying, talk too much and overthink too little, and you are safe in the knowledge that you are loved at your worst and best and every in between. 

the kind of friendship that meets you exactly where you are and celebrates you for it. the kind where you text the next day and say sorry if i was too much, and you get words like this in return. 

for every terrible thing i’ve faced, i was given the exact right people to get me through it. 

a pretty damn good friendship indeed. 💙

I found a great big love. I wasn’t patient and it didn’t surprise me. 

I used to watch movies and think “when will it be my turn?” 

Now I watch them and think “it doesn’t hold a candle.”

Slow pain. It’s so boring. So tedious. The grief over losing my childhood home comes in drips, not waves. 

I had my big dramatic moment where I cried my eyes out and Dom held me like he could keep me together— so dramatic that we laughed about it after. 

Music was playing. “That was so fucking sad,” he said, “I don’t think I can ever listen to that song again.” And we threw our heads back and laughed until we fell asleep. 

It was so satisfying. I replay it sometimes. I know Dom does, too. He says we get a few big “I love you’s” in our lives and one of his happened that night. 

I was so sad, last night in the home I’d grown up in, not sure how to let it go or if I even could, and I couldn’t believe how unlonely all of it felt by his side. 

I told him I loved him right then and he says he still thinks about it. “I could tell you really meant it.”

It was perfect. Cathartic. And I’m still sad. I’m still sad. I am just fine. Everyone is safe and fine. I’ll never go home again. We’re watching my favorite show like I used to in my bedroom. I’ll never go home again. 

“Can we watch it when we go to your house?” Yes, he says. Of course we can. 

And it sounds like I love you. He means it.

Now approaching thirty. Would it be cliche to say I’m feeling everything they warned us about? Sounds dull and I always thought I was rare.

It feels bizarre to realize I’m living a section of my life I only ever associated with sitcom characters and my parents. I have been to my high school reunion. I am of an age where we need to be reunited. 

I have now been to the weddings of most of the people I used to sit up with late at night to imagine what our weddings would look like. I am living through the days that felt impossibly far off. “One day” is current and I’m in it. 

And I say I’m not failing but everyone I know lives in a nicer apartment. Everyone I know has a job they like and are good at. Feels like half of them have a job they love and are famous for. And I have a doctors appointment every day and that’s not a hyperbole, it’s literal. 

Is this to be expected? Did you all feel it? Am I texting the group chat to ask if it’s cliche to come of age in your late twenties? Is cliche just a negative word to describe what is my actual favorite feeling which is never being alone?

I can barely scroll through the pictures of everyone smiling— I used to be so nosy. I loved to see what you were smiling about. Now everyone’s a marker to measure myself against. Should I have that by now? Should I want it?

I duck in and duck out just to post my own picture of myself smiling. hi. I’m out here. I’m a little freaked out. I’m a little happy. I’m a little bit concerned about the wrinkles that are forming around my smile but I’m trying not to fixate on that. I’ll see you at the next reunion.

At nineteen I had outgrown myself. My bedroom, my hair, my hometown. Everyone I knew on earth lived within twenty minutes of each other. 

I was such a product of proximity; baptized with my best friend because I wanted to go wherever she did, even after death. Have you ever loved someone so much that suddenly you believed in God? 

I applied to the schools everyone did and went to the school everyone did and then I moved far away forever, partly because I wanted to and partly because I always said I would.

And I never looked back except all the time. I still like her. I hope that she likes me.

photo is still one of my very favorites by @juliadurr 💛

I’m always told I favor my mom. Same hands, same eyes, same hair. But I found this picture of my dad a few weeks ago from when he was just a little boy, and I recognized myself.

My dad is more than just my dad. A thing that every child eventually realizes, the same way I am more than just his daughter. 

And I’ve always asked him for stories from when he was a kid, always wondered if I was like him. Am I like him? 

He is a person entirely separate from my perception of him. And there I was, thinking he woke up in the dark to pull the sun up every morning for the rest of us. 

I brought the picture downstairs to show Dom. Hang on, I said, this reminds me of something. And I dug around in my phone until I found a picture of me at the same age.

“Look at us. We lost our teeth the same year.” The little boy with missing teeth who would one day hide quarters under my pillow. We look mischievous. Same slotted grin. 

Everyone knows how I knocked my teeth out. He lost his playing hockey, and then flipping over his bike. 

And I look like him. I’m just like him.

little post to celebrate that i am done with superficial radiation therapy!! (and also to hard launch the fact that i had a little skin cancer!!!)

back in february my dermotologist discovered a cancerous spot on my nose. it was basal cell carcinoma, the most treatable type of skin cancer, but the location made it very tricky. 

for the last six weeks i have been getting srt (superficial radiation therapy) every single week day. because it’s only skin deep it’s not as intense as “traditional” radiation. (i think. but i am not an expert so please don’t take my word for it and talk to a doctor if you’re going through anything like this!!)

i mostly kept it a secret because i wasn’t ready to hear everyone’s opinions and also because i was determined to work through it and keep auditioning. i picked a competitive life in a competitive industry and i didn’t really want anyone to know until it was over and i could prove everything was fine.

it’s been a weird mix of feeling lucky it wasn’t worse and unlucky that it happened at all. it was hard and it made me tired. it was a little scary. i never went to an appointment alone. mostly it was frustrating to deal with on top of all of the medical stuff that’s already going on. i felt a little vain about it all. i didn’t want my face to change. i didn’t want to complain too loudly because i was the youngest and healthiest person in every waiting room. 

this is a rare occurrence in young people but it happens, especially if you’re fair skinned and freckled, and especially if you are on medications that put you at risk for skin cancer like i am. 

check your side effects, keep up with your appointments, wear a lot of sunscreen and extend as much grace as you can to the people who do all of those things and end up here anyway. it isn’t fun. but, like most things that aren’t, i’m proud of how i’ve handled it. 💚 yay!!!

The loss of the house is more than just the house. You lose all the little rituals of thirty years of homecoming: the left turn, the twin pine trees, the wet smell of the bayou. The grocery store where the boy who asked you to homecoming worked. The driveway where you had your first kiss. 

I’ll come back, but I won’t go inside. I’ll come back sometime but it will be rare instead of familiar. 

I have taken the most mundane habits of my life— the circular path I learned to ride my bike, the street I learned to drive my car, the swings I would race to in the twilight to meet up with my best friends— and turned them sacred and strange. Something to be held up to the light and examined. Something to explain in detail to the man who loves me, when it used to just be walking home.

And when I return now it will be to the river, not the coast. This neighborhood will be a place I’ll visit. It will not be the place I mean when I say “I’m going back home.”

My mom drove me to the house she grew up in once. She pointed out the curb where she had her first kiss. We circled the block and I pictured her, the woman who raised me, as a little girl.

I asked if it made her sad to come back, but I knew her like a story. How in that terrifying moment when she stepped out of her front door all her favorite days were ahead of her still, waiting.

She just smiled, and then she laughed.

I’m worried that I’m wasting my happiness feeling like I don’t deserve it. There are so many things that are difficult; can’t I let this one be good?

We spend the weekend inside, we cancel our plans. Every night when the heat pulls back just enough we walk a different zigzag path through the neighborhood. The sky and the trees look just like I pictured they would on humid summer nights in Texas when I wished for this. Sometimes it’s so perfectly what I asked for my eyes won’t adjust to it.

And he’s so perfectly what I asked for my heart can’t adjust to it. He reads like all the heroes of my favorite novels but better. At night when I weep over a world real or imagined I lay my head on his chest and he doesn’t pull away until I do. He is my safest place on earth but looking at an old picture of him still makes my stomach hurt; I used to lose sleep over if he liked me back.

And can I just enjoy it? Us, in the summer, four years in and trading stories of the first two weeks— tell me what you thought of me then. What do you think of me now? And walking the same neighborhood and sitting on the same couch where he told me of all the people in the world he’d met he liked me best. 

The feeling when the perfect person says all the perfect things, like I only half absorb it. Right after I smile I worry how it could be taken away.

I found this old message from my dad, sort of uncharacteristically earnest. I hope you find someone who makes you as happy as your mom makes me, he said. It’s waiting for you, he said. At the time he sent it I had been single for five years. I fell in love with Dom later that month. 

There is so much to worry about, and I’ve always been good at that. But us walking under palm trees in the summer? Nowhere new, just the neighborhood streets cracked and shimmering.

And us, on the same path. If I never got anything else I asked for, that would be enough.

I had the kind of dream that seems so obvious upon waking. I was in between these two apartments in the hallway— in one was a costume party thrown with the vigor of every college house party I had ever been to. The lights were low, everyone was dancing, I was looking for Kristen and Kiki inside but I couldn’t find them. I was looking to bring them to the other room.

And in the other room— my childhood park after it rained. My mom leaning a hip against her car in the parking lot, Kelsey on the swing. We were little again. “I don’t know what’s taking them so long,” I said, even though I did know. We just kicked at the sand that had turned to mud for a while until the sun broke through the clouds. 

Everything shimmered so beautifully that I asked my mom and Kelsey if they had their phones on them and they just looked at me blankly. It was time to get in the car, twist our knobby knees together in the backseat. 

Drive for years and years to meet myself at a party in the future. I didn’t want the afternoon to end. But it was alright. I was looking forward to it. Kristen and Kiki were there.
more grateful for these moments than i could ever possibly say

The first half of summer shed its skin too easily. I lost it in between appointments, filed it away with the bills and save the dates. I forgot to post it on the fridge where I could look at it every day, really savor the fact that it came around again to call. 

First year in six that the weather at Disneyland wasn’t my main concern. I didn’t read by the pool, I didn’t drive back and forth from Burbank as the sun set with chlorine in my hair, I didn’t save my money and go to Europe. I cleaned my house and took sweaty naps on top of the covers. I slowly and methodically fried layers off the right side of my nose.

We kicked up our feet in protest. I couldn’t work or hope for work. I felt like the smallest part of the biggest thing. I got better. 

The second half of summer unfurled like a blossom around me. We celebrated little wins. We partied hard once or twice to forget the other nights. We sat in the sun but it wasn’t the same as before I learned what days in the sun could lead to. 

It’s the last summer of my twenties. The first five were the pits, they were a ride. The last five were a lesson in letting you hold my hand. 

And it ended in a promise that I might as well have made five years ago, that night you sat on my couch. The gift you gave me then: how to be sure of something again. 

So the weather will change but not everything else. Turns out some things do stick around.

I’ve been dreaming in metaphors. There are huge spiders loose in the apartment; I can’t rest until they’re caught. Dom is trapping them under glass for me and I wake up in the middle of asking him even the big one? The huge one? You got it, you promise?

And lately my phone feels radioactive. It’s hot in my hand all the time. The days are shrinking and all my unearned potential is deflating in front of me. Is this just three weeks before thirty? Is this just so overdone?

Maybe we put that down for a while, Dom says to the phone when my knuckles turn white around it. But who will tell me about Taylor Swift! I will, he says. Who will tell me what everyone is saying? I will. 

But his hands are full. He’s already catching spiders. 

I’m like the princess and the pea, I tell him. I let one thing go wrong and mess all the rest up. I can’t enjoy anything if everything’s not in order. 

A migraine is not a pea, he tells me. It’s the whole bed. Go easy. 

In the car we pass a sign that says “Thank a soldier today.” Dom pats my head. “Thank you.” We laugh so hard the steam comes off a little and then we go to Target. A millennial bandaid. I pick out two new books. 

So this is where my twenties chewed me up and spit me out:

I am joined when I laugh. I am held when I cry. I am no longer alone at the end of a bad day. I guess I am still in the book section of Target.
sweater is on, spells are cast, and october has informed me that it is just, in fact, getting started

I used to read like my life depended on it, like I was white-knuckled gripping the pages saying get me out of here right now. 

Used to open my hands in the middle of a sob and Dom would race to deliver whatever was currently holding my bookmark, instant transportation for up to an hour if I was really lucky. 

When the migraines came they came from behind, gripping the back of my skull and wrapping long fingers around to my temples. 

It is not instantaneous. They creep in like a thought. Something I was meant to remember; oh yes, I am a girl in pain. 

They took everything in pieces. My spontaneity, my easy way of being, some favorite foods and drinks, and the subject of so many conversations that I often wonder what else it is I would’ve talked about had this never happened to me at all. 

They came for reading last. Or rather, they came for it in my most desperate hours.

Gone were the books I would read on my phone, the print too small and the blue light glasses I purchased dizzying me even after I took them off. 

Hardbacks went next— too heavy to hold open for hours at a time, my neck stiff and tender from the way I flexed my arms so imperceptibly. 

I tried audiobooks but it wasn’t the same, I was always where I was, never as transported and forgotten. I went for long walks but could never forget my feet. 

So I took to paperbacks, small enough to fit in my bag. I took to poetry. It’s lighter. 

I miss heavy sentences. I miss run ons, thoughts on thoughts, I miss not being me. Not tapering down each experience to be just tolerable enough. 

And on the days I have a clear head and a good book, the pages feel more hollow. I resent their happy endings, how their dreams fall into place and any mention of a headache only needs a sentence or two to be forgotten.

It’s such a strange thing to describe, how I’ve lived through difficult things but chronic pain has undone me so completely. 

I don’t know how else to say it but that it’s always there now, holding court, making little changes to everything I thought was fundamental. I am never without it. 

One day it came and took the books.

It’s the last day of my twenties!

This is normally where I write a big thing about how it felt to be the age I was before I move into the next one. But a decade feels like a lot to sum up. 

I remember turning twenty so clearly. I wanted to live in California. I remember sitting next to Nathan in my last days of nineteen and saying “can you believe we’re about to be in our twenties?? This is the time when so much is going to happen. I might even meet the person I’m going to marry.” 

I was in my checkered purple pajamas, still sharing a bedroom. In two more years I’d move to LA and into the room that the person I do in fact get to marry joins me in a few years and a pandemic later.

I’m obsessed with a good coming of age story. If you know me you know that’s my comfort. I reread and rewatch and visit them like bucket list vacations. I think that’s why I built my own on here, writing everything down the way I did. 

I can’t believe I have my twenties captured like this in this virtual diary. I can’t believe I can go back and watch the videos and talk about the nights like episodes of my favorite show. 

This apartment has been my apartment since I was twenty-two. This couch has been the couch we all have at various points and for various reasons thrown up on and where Dom sat across from me one October morning and told me that he wanted to be more than friends. The same couch we collapsed upon at two in the morning the night he proposed to laugh about all the little hints I had missed. 

I have watched my whole life unfold here. My very own coming of age. A story that would never have existed had I not left my hometown— I had to pick out every single piece myself.

And it’s so full. It’s so full. And it’s mine. 

I’m going to come back to this one. I’m going to read it over and over and over again.

I was trudging through, as always on my very best behavior, tripping over disappointments tangled up like tree roots; fundamental to my very foundation. 

But see, I’m good at this— I never stay down, my feet never stay still, my smile never falters. Grief peeks through on the briefest occasions and I meet it then leave it behind because it simply can’t keep up. 

Oh the effort it takes to enjoy myself. I wish they could see how much planning goes in to every joyful moment. I can do it, it will just be harder. 

There will be easy outs and checkpoints and rescue missions and if it all goes off perfectly see the pictured above: a moment stolen back. 

The pain will take and take and take— but I have talents, too. 

I can steal it back.

Back when I was twenty-two, when I had fled to New Zealand to outrun a heartbreak that had driven a stake clean through my optimism, back when every person I met had to hear the story of how I fell in love and was crushed then crushed again, my roommate told me something so profound that I carried it with me over seas and continents and years. 

She looked at me sideways, the way I was pulled together in slivers, zipped up in my parka and doubled over in the cold. We were walking back through the neighborhood streets to our shared apartment. “Shannon,” she said, “I don’t think you do this again.”

“Live abroad? Definitely not.” Hood up, hunched against the wind. Adventure did not become me. 

“No,” she said, “all of this. Another breakup.” And she gestured to the mess of me, and we sort of laughed in that early twenties way where it was okay to be that unhappy, and I said something like why, because I’m such a pleasure? Because I’m clearly handling it all so well?

She smiled. She was so easy to be with. God, I envied that about her. I had never felt more difficult. But she smiled at me like I was in fact a pleasure— like I was an idiot for never noticing. 

“I just think you marry the next one.”

We laughed but inside I thought, really? Really? Could that happen? And it always stuck in my brain. It was A Thing for many years after, that Shannon didn’t date. I was overly cautious but maybe I was also just biding my time. 

And she was, like she is with most things, right. 

Hear that, Katie? I always remembered what you said. 

I’m gonna marry this one. 

I concede. You were right about everything. You always are.
